column1: Will any 2020 California election results be altered by a cyberattack against a voting system?
column6: ['Society', 'Security and Conflict']
Prob << 1%

The California 2020 elections will not be altered directly by a cyberattack. This is largely due to the fact that because of the events of the 2016 elections the government has invested heavily in cyber defense systems. California also has a measure put in place to verify whether the votes were altered. However, seeing as the Presidential election already passed, there was no incident of a cyber attack. Therefore proving that no election results would be altered.
Passage of time update
consensus since a lot of weeks
just due to history of elections with cyber attacks

Election security is very high in the United States and there was no tampering with the 2020 general election results. (https://www.npr.org/sections/live-updates-2020-election-results/2020/11/12/934377227/no-evidence-election-was-compromised-cybersecurity-agency-says) Given this high level of cybersecurity it is extremely unlikely that election results in California will be altered.

No. The voting systems themselves are tricky targets with all sorts of verifying mechanisms. Also they are widely spread out. Combine that with a new US Cyber Czar who knows what he is talking about and also Russia needing to figure out how to deal with a new administration.

I'm going with a zero assessment on this question because, while I think it highly unlikely that the 2020 CA elections were cyber-manipulated to the degree it changed any outcome/totals, I find it even more unlikely that CA would be aware of it in time for this question to close, given the rate of attacks compared to the rate of detection. These are my three primary data points: Hackers attack every 39 seconds, on average 2,244 times a day. (University of Maryland) The average time to identify a breach in 2019 was 206 days. (IBM) The average lifecycle of a breach was 314 days (from the breach to containment). (IBM) Since the time from the presidential election to the close of this question is 184 days, less than both of the averages of 206 and the 314 days, plus the info from @juancambeiro on CISA's election confidence, leads me to my 0 assessment.

"Christopher Krebs, the nation's former top election security official, tells 'Axios on HBO' that President Trump is spreading disinformation ... [Trump] fired him for putting out a statement saying that the 2020 election was the most secure in American history ... Krebs had refused to co-sign — and in fact publicly contradicted — Trump's conspiracy theories that hacked computer systems flipped the election by switching votes from Trump to Joe Biden." https://www.axios.com/christopher-krebs-trump-2020-election-a40eec9d-a32a-4a04-824f-5ec13ba7f6e6.html
this is a nonsense claim which the courts will not accept

Passage of time update
CISA has been very confident in its assessments. This certainly isn’t impossible but it sure looks unlikely.

New statement out today by officials from the Department of Homeland Security's Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency (CISA) and its election partners: "The November 3rd election was the most secure in American history. Right now, across the country, election officials are reviewing and double checking the entire election process prior to finalizing the result ... There is no evidence that any voting system deleted or lost votes, changed votes, or was in any way compromised." https://www.cisa.gov/news/2020/11/12/joint-statement-elections-infrastructure-government-coordinating-council-election
There is still no indication that this has occurred.

"Three and a half years of election security upgrades, training and government information sharing appeared to pay off on Election Day as voting unfolded with the usual technical glitches but no evidence of successful cyberattacks ... Even so, officials cautioned that the election process still faced serious cyber threats as it moved from the vote-casting phase into the vote-counting phase ... University of Michigan computer science professor J. Alex Halderman, one of the country’s most respected voting security experts, wrote on Twitter that 'the vote counting is an *even more* important area of vulnerability now, and will continue to be until the election result is clear,' because adversaries now have a clear sense of 'where they need to intervene to affect the outcome' ... But regardless of what happens next, surprisingly little happened on Tuesday" [1].

(no change) An idea I alluded to yesterday: "While officials have warned all year about possible cyberattacks—and clearly Iran and Russia are already engaging in some—the worst-case scenarios of hackers actually changing votes seem unlikely. Instead, the biggest cyber threat is likely from groups pretending that they changed votes." quoted from:

"White House National Security Adviser Robert O’Brien declared on Sunday that Russian hackers who were recently reported to have launched attacks on state and local governments 'can’t change votes' in the Nov. 3 elections." https://www.politico.com/news/2020/10/25/obrien-hackers-votes-november-election-432268
Down 1% for passage of time.

We are told by the government (federal and state) that voting systems are secure. Everybody is aware of the potential hacking by various state players such as Russia, China, and Iran, and presumably doing their utmost effort preventing this to happen. I trust that California is rich enough and have the resources to implement mediation efforts.

There was one congressional district decided by 3% or less and 2 by 5% in 2018. Due to redlining and demographics, California politics is very polarized with most victories by margins of over 20%. If a cyberattack were to change an election result in most California districts, the results would be extremely scrutinized and research. The organization responsible for the attack will most likely brought to light and the attack would be too obvious to dispute. States and counties that have tighter margins are more likely to be attack than districts in CA.

"Microsoft has taken legal steps to dismantle one of the world’s largest botnets, an effort it says is aimed at thwarting criminal hackers who might seek to snarl state and local computer systems used to maintain voter rolls or report on election results. ... The fear isn’t that an attack could alter actual results, but rather that it could shake the confidence of voters ... Reporting systems or voter-registration sites are easier targets for hackers than the actual systems that count the ballots, which governments have worked to harden over the years." https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2020/10/12/microsoft-trickbot-ransomware/

DHS in USA is warning of ransomware (primarily trickbot) attacks “could significantly disrupt the upcoming elections”. US cyber command (CYBERCOM) is conducting operation to hinder trickbot botnet during election (they can only hinder a few hours at time if I understand correctly). Have a longer report containing interesting info... . China, Russia, Iran up to old tricks . Registration data and voter history of ~10 million voters (mostly Michigan) available on dark net . State sponsored actors exploiting vulnerabilities “resulting in unauthorized access to election support systems” however FBI and CISA assert “no evidence to date integrity of elections data compromised”
Down 1% for passage of time.

In the event that a cyber attack happens or if the election results are contested claiming cyberattack, it's not clear from the question as to what availability of evidence really means. Even if there is evidence that cyber attack happened which affected the total count / election outcome, there will be a long drawn investigation to resolve this and given the time it took to prove the famous Russia interference / collusion in 2016 election, it's highly unlikely that this would be proven by May 2021. My forecast is based on the fact that historically there's no evidence of this event. While a cyberattack is likely, the probability of it affecting results is negligible and probability of this getting proved within 6 months is also highly unlikely.
There's a chance

I receive most cyber threat/crime reports as part of my job. Have yet to receive any credible threats re. Hacking of election in California. I did, however receive the following today which aligns with disinformation campaigns... “Alleged Iranian interference operations aimed to disrupt U.S. Presidential elections . Intelligence sources observing Iran-linked activity... . Iran sees election as impacting its economic and social stability . This is attributed to Trump administration’s reimposition of sanctions on Iran which have resulted in increased levels of economic and social hardships and an increased threat of a direct military engagement with the U.S. . Tehran views the re-election of President Donald Trump as leading to further instability and greater economic challenges . Conservative Iranian elements also criticized a possible new administration led by former Vice President Joe Biden as one that will not alter attempts to isolate the Islamic Republic . Intelligence sources claim Iranian covert disinformation operations relating to the U.S. electoral process were carried out using automated bot accounts and fake personas on social media (ex. “Endless Mayfly” campaign . Overt Iranian information operations have rapidly established programs such as English language “Palestine Files” which adjoined U.S. topics like Black Lives Matter and the death of George Floyd with that of pro-Palestinian and “anti-Zionist” movements. . Such operations broadly contribute to Iran’s objective of deteriorating the U.S. government reputation . Iranian media groups like Press TV use investigative reporting and interviews with U.S. based persons on topics such as domestic politics and social developments to depict perspectives that support Iran’s interests . Intelligence sources assess these efforts are specifically aimed at English-speaking audiences, primarily in the U.S., with the goal of lowering the audience’s confidence in the democratic process . Cyber operations have also impacted the U.S. election space, showcased by reports of Iranian state-sponsored threat actor APT35 conducting phishing attacks against the campaign staff of President Donald Trump in June 2020.” It goes on with further details but you get the gist... the above information did not come from the U.S. It is possible another state actor influenced it however (dis-disinformation?). Just because your paranoid, doesn’t mean they’re not after you!

Regardless of the election outcomes I expect it will be contested. But admitting there was a hack would seriously undermine the system. Also, as others have said, why attack a non battleground state.

At this time it will appears that an attack that alters votes is unlikely. However, an attack that suppresses voter turnout or makes counting votes more difficult is very likely.

California votes primarily on paper ballots. 1% audit of the paper is required in all elections making it extremely unlikely that a hack would go unnoticed, and no election outcomes would be changed due to the ability to recount paper ballots.
It's a possibility. I would be more concerned about alterations in a swing state, where it would be harder to detect, as it might be less expected.

this question is poorly defined, to me. What does 'results be altered' mean? Does it mean the election is swayed from D to R in a particular seat, or that 1 bad vote is tallied and later disqualified? If an election outcome is swung, it necessarily means vote totals were adjusted, or votes were moved from one person to another.
It's possible - but why target California where an anomaly in results would be clearly seen?
In the unlikely event that there is a successful cyberattack - it likely will be caught promptly
This article doesn’t specifically address an attack but does outline measures to verify numbers etc. https://www.wired.com/story/election-mass-voter-fraud-protections/

I receive multiple daily reports re vulnerabilities (real and potential) and latest attack vectors. Some very bright people behind these (in turn state actors like APT). And they are successful in monetization. But, in terms of elections, more bang for buck in misleading information...including potential voting hacks. Will look into more, but for now I’m going low at 1%. Wouldn’t California be odd - elections are usually wrapped up before their results roll in?
(1) The odds are that people who know how to interfere with US voting results at a meaningful level are roughly as numerous as centaurs.

While not a zero probability, I'm rounding down to zero. The idea of hacking the voting systems is what security expert Bruce Schneier calls a "movie-plot threat". It's something that the bad guys do in movies (or in the minds of unhinged politicians and commentators), but not in the real world. The same outcome can be achieved with far less effort by other means.

The first two key considerations are the following: 1) Who has the motive to launch cyberattack(s) on California's election infrastructure? 2) Who has the capability to successfully carry out such an attack? I think foreign state actors that are hostile to US interests meet both of these criteria. In particular, I think Russia is especially likely to carry out such an attack given its unprecedented meddling in the 2016 presidential election.
the arrogance of our politicians and computer people can't be underestimated
seems to me to be based on 3 probabilities (similar to @MRVDM12)
Initial guess
Base rate on this one is 0%.

In reality, this is a combination of four probabilities: (1) the probability of this cyber attack being attempted (2) the probability of this cyber attack being good enough to succeed, yet clumsy enough to leave behind some evidence (3) the probability of this evidence being discovered before the deadline (1st of May 2021) (4) the probability that whoever finds this evidence (FBI? NSA?) will make (some of) it public before the deadline
As a large democratic state it may be an appealing target for state-level actors seeking to influence the election; however this is balanced by the robustness of its' state institutions.

I note that the question refers to a cyberattack against any voting system in a Californian election whether it be Federal , State or Local. The immediate focus is on the Presidential election on November 3rd, but there are other elections to be held on that date. Depending on the type of election will possibly determine the probability, source and likelihood of a cyberattack. All elections are potentially susceptible to an attack and therefore the result could be affected. Looking at the register of elections to be carried out in California in the remaining part of 2020, there appears to be just November 3rd, that is for the General Election, school boards, DA and Superior Court and possibly other minor appointments. The Federal election appears to have postal vote issues that could be manipulated. Possible, but not likely due to an awareness, trained officials and a paper trail as dictated by Californian law. School Boards could be hacked by tech savvy students. Is this possible? – Yes. The District Attorney and Superior Court appointments could be the focus of criminal elements. Is this possible? Yes. According to the findings of the referenced websites, local officials lack the skills or training to monitor malpractices, potential or otherwise. The attacks themselves could be an attempt to distort results emanating from the system itself, such as voting lists/postal ballots, lobbying influential parties or creating rumours and innuendo via social media. The result of the latter being a creation of a disillusionment and distrust in the system by declining to vote at all, which would affect the result of the vote. If the result of any election held in California had been affected by a cyberattack, would it be discovered? Perhaps not and that is why 3%. https://ballotpedia.org/California_elections,_2020
Down 3% to be closer to the consensus.
California ain't Georgia or Florida. So the odds of California's election results being altered as the result of a cyber attack are very low, virtually nil.

Although campaigns have been subject to cyber attacks (1), there have not previously been (afaict) cyber attacks aimed at any election which have been discovered to have altered the election results. Given the base rate, the difficulty of doing so initially, the difficulty of being detected and the low pay off of altering the election results in california I think this has a <1% of occurring.
I'm sure that there will be some attacks. I don't think they will change vote totals or outcome.
Hat-tip to @lsgold7 for analysis which gave me some additional confidence. Nothing is foolproof, but paper is a solid place to start.

There's some probability of it happening I guess but less than 0.5%, so rounding down to zero. Nothing is 100% secure but changing vote totals would be a difficult task given the security precautions taken.
